Exploring the BRFSS data

Gabriele Grasso

28 November 2019

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(knitr)
knitr::opts_chunk$set(warning=FALSE)

Load data

load("brfss2013.RData")

Part 1: Data

The database used in this exploratory data analysis (EDA) exercise results from the survey conducted by the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) of the unhospitalized adult population of the United States of America and some of its territories. This survey concerns preventive health practices and behaviors linked to chronic diseases. Detailed information can be found on this link. The results of this survey are generalizable to the unhospitalized adult American population because the respondents have been randomly sampled. However, it is not possible to establish a link of causality between different variables because these are not the results of an experimental study, i.e. participants are not subject to random assignment.

Part 2: Research questions

Research question 1:

It is common experience that sleeping enough is essential to a good quality of life. But how much do people sleep? Are such variables as gender and general health condition correlated to the number of sleeping hours per night?

Research question 2:

High cholesterol levels are a risk factor for cardio-vascular disease. It is therefore important to check this level regularly in order to prevent serious problems. Is a person’s education level correlated to the awareness of the problem posed by cholesterol?

Research question 3:

Physical activity of any kind is often credited with improving the mood and overall physical health. Is there a correlation between the number of days in a month in which respondents reported to have performed a physical activity and the number of days in which they reported poor physical or mental health?

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Research question 1:

As a first exploratory step, we will plot the distribution of number of sleeping hours for the male and the female population.

male_sleeping_hours <- brfss2013 %>% filter(sex == 'Male', sleptim1 <= 24)
female_sleeping_hours <- brfss2013 %>% filter(sex == 'Female', sleptim1 <= 24)
ggplot(mapping = aes(x,y)) + 
geom_bar(data = male_sleeping_hours, aes(x =sleptim1, y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)*100), fill='purple') + 
geom_bar(data = female_sleeping_hours, aes(x =sleptim1, y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)*100), 
width = 0.5,fill = 'green') +
xlab('Sleeping hours') + ylab('Percentage of respondents') + theme_bw() + 
annotate("text", x = 12, y = 21, label = "Male", colour = 'purple') +  
annotate("text", x = 12, y = 22.5, label = "Female", colour = 'green')

Interestingly, the two distributions are close, but the relative majority of men declares to sleep on average 7 hours per night, whereas the relative majority of women declares to sleep 8 hours. Next we will use box plots to show how the number of sleeping hours correlates to general health condition in the male population.

boxplot(sleptim1~genhlth , data = male_sleeping_hours, xlab = "General Health",
        ylab = "Sleeping Hours", main = "Male Population")

As can be seen, the distributions are very similar for all health conditions from Excellent to Fair, whereas in case of Poor health the minimum and the first quartile are lower, but the maximum is higher. This suggest that Poor health is related to many different kinds of sleep trouble.

The same data visualization can be made for the female population.

boxplot(sleptim1~genhlth , data = female_sleeping_hours, xlab = "General Health", 
        ylab = "Sleeping Hours", main = "Female Population")

In this case, women reporting Excellent health have a shorter inter-quartile range of sleeping hours than other categories, although the median is the same from Excellent to Fair health. As in the previous case, the upper and lower bounds of the distribution of sleeping hours among women who report Poor health are wider than for the other categories.

Research question 2:

In order to answer the second research question, we will calculate the fraction of respondents having ever had blood cholesterol checked for each education level. The results are presented in the following table.

table1 <- table(brfss2013$educa, brfss2013$bloodcho)
edu_bc <- as.data.frame.matrix(prop.table(table1, margin=1))
edu_bc <- add_rownames(edu_bc, "Education")
kable(edu_bc,  caption = 'Ever Had Blood Cholesterol Checked')
Ever Had Blood Cholesterol Checked
Education Yes No
Never attended school or only kindergarten 0.7324159 0.2675841
Grades 1 through 8 (Elementary) 0.8031919 0.1968081
Grades 9 though 11 (Some high school) 0.7929594 0.2070406
Grade 12 or GED (High school graduate) 0.8502907 0.1497093
College 1 year to 3 years (Some college or technical school) 0.8749696 0.1250304
College 4 years or more (College graduate) 0.9241134 0.0758866

It appears that at most 80% of people having lower education level (from none to some high-school) have ever had their cholesterol checked. This fraction increases to 92% for college graduates, showing a positive correlation between education level and cholesterol awareness. It is also interesting to see how check results vary with education level. The next table shows the fraction of people who were ever told that their blood cholesterol was high, for each education level.

table2 <- table(brfss2013$educa, brfss2013$toldhi2)
edu_tc <- as.data.frame.matrix(prop.table(table2, margin=1))
edu_tc <- add_rownames(edu_tc, "Education")
kable(edu_tc, caption = 'Ever Told Blood Cholesterol High')
Ever Told Blood Cholesterol High
Education Yes No
Never attended school or only kindergarten 0.5330490 0.4669510
Grades 1 through 8 (Elementary) 0.5473786 0.4526214
Grades 9 though 11 (Some high school) 0.5135047 0.4864953
Grade 12 or GED (High school graduate) 0.4711461 0.5288539
College 1 year to 3 years (Some college or technical school) 0.4353215 0.5646785
College 4 years or more (College graduate) 0.3940735 0.6059265

Slightly more than 50% of people who have none to elementary education were told that they had high cholesterol at least once in their life. This percentage descends with the level of education to 39% for college graduates. This also suggests a positive correlation between education level and cholesterol awareness.

Research question 3:

We will use three variables in answering the third research question. The first is a categorical variable (‘Yes’ or ‘No’) indicating if the respondents have performed any physical activity in the past 30 days or not. The other two variables represent the number of days in the past thirty in which the respondents suffered either poor physical or mental health, respectively. Preliminary statistics, reported below, show that - on average - people who have done physical activity in the previous month have also reported less days of poor physical and mental health.

brfss2013 %>% filter(!is.na(exerany2)) %>% group_by(exerany2) %>% 
summarise(phys_days_mean = mean(physhlth, na.rm = TRUE), 
phys_days_sd = sd(physhlth, na.rm = TRUE), ment_days_mean = mean(menthlth, na.rm = TRUE), 
ment_days_sd = sd(menthlth, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   exerany2 phys_days_mean phys_days_sd ment_days_mean ment_days_sd
##   <fct>             <dbl>        <dbl>          <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1 Yes                3.23         7.48           2.84         6.91
## 2 No                 7.38        11.2            4.76         9.29

It is difficult, however to draw any conclusion from the previous results because the standard deviations associated to each mean value are too high. For this reason we will once again make use of box plots. The following plot concerns the distribution of days of poor physical health in the month prior to the interview.

boxplot(physhlth~exerany2, data = brfss2013, xlab = "Did Exercise in Past 30 Days", 
        ylab = "Number Of Days Physical Health Not Good")

It can be seen that the median of the distribution is equal to zero, meaning that at least 50% of the respondents did not declare any day of poor physical health, irrespectively of the physical activity. However, 25% people who did exercise in the previous 30 days declare at most 2 days of poor physical health and the remaining 25% declares at most 5 five days (not taking the outliers into account). The situation is quite different for the group of people who did not do any physical exercise. The third quartile corresponds to 10 days of poor physical health and the maximum to 27 days. Therefore, there seems to be a correlation between physical health and exercise, although the present data do not allow to make any inference of causality.

The next box plots concern the distribution of days of poor mental health depending on physical exercise.

boxplot(menthlth~exerany2, data = brfss2013, xlab = "Did Exercise in Past 30 Days", 
        ylab = "Number Of Days Mental Health Not Good")

For the people of have done physical exercise, the distribution of days of poor mental health is the same as that of poor physical health, presented in the previous graphic. However, for the people who did not do physical exercise, the third quartile corresponds to 5 days and the maximum to 10 days. This suggests a more tenuous correlation between physical exercise and mental health than between exercise and physical health.
